{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Dr Carol Christian | honorific_suffix = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|12|28}} | birth_place = [[Cincinnati]], Ohio, United States | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | nationality = American | fields = Astronomy | workplaces = [[Space Telescope Science Institute]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[Boston University]] | thesis_title = Investigations of distant field stars and clusters in the galactic anticenter | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = 1979 | doctoral_advisor = Kenneth Janes | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | website = {{URL|www.stsci.edu/~carolc/}} | footnotes = }} '''Carol Ann Christian''' (born 28 December 1950) is an American astronomer and [[science communicator]], who works for the [[Space Telescope Science Institute]] (STScI; the science operations center for the [[Hubble Space Telescope]]) as a scientist on the institute's outreach program.
Christian was born in [[Cincinnati]], Ohio, and studied astronomy and physics at [[Boston University]], from which she graduated with a PhD in 1979 with a thesis on ''Investigations of distant field stars and clusters in the galactic anticenter''.<ref name="bulib">{{cite web|title=Investigations of distant field stars and clusters in the galactic anticenter|url=http://buprimo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?tabs=requestTab&ct=display&fn=search&doc=ALMA_BOSU121612692810001161&indx=1&recIds=ALMA_BOSU121612692810001161&recIdxs=0&elementId=0&renderMode=poppedOut&displayMode=full&frbrVersion=&vid=BU&institution=BOSU&query=any%2Ccontains%2C99176783890001161&vl(173035485UI0)=any&dscnt=0&scp.scps=scope%3A%28AZBOSU%29%2Cscope%3A%28BOSU%29%2Cscope%3A%28CRBU%29%2Cscope%3A%28ALMA_BOSU1%29%2Cprimo_central_multiple_fe&vl(freeText0)=99176783890001161&vl(1UIStartWith0)=contains&dstmp=1459737784634|publisher=Boston University Libraries|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref> She then worked as an astronomer for [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name="istcoll">{{cite web|title=Fall 2007 Colloquium Series|url=https://istcolloq.gsfc.nasa.gov/fall2007/speaker/christian.html|website=IS&T Colloquium Series|publisher=[[NASA]]|accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>
In August 1995, Christian was selected as the first head of STScI's new Office of Public Outreach after a national search.<ref name="madsen">{{cite book|last1=Madsen|first1=Claus; edited by André Heck|title=Astronomy Communication|date=2003|publisher=[[Springer Netherlands]]|location=Dordrecht|isbn=9401708010}}</ref> She has continued to act as an outreach scientist for the institute as a media spokesperson, educator and author. From 2003 to 2006, she worked as a scientific policy advisor for the [[United States Department of State|State Department]]. In 2010, she co-authored ''[[A Question and Answer Guide to Astronomy]]'' with Pierre-Yves Bely and Jean-René Roy.<ref name="skyatnight">{{cite news|title=A Question & Answer Guide To Astronomy|url=http://www.skyatnightmagazine.com/book/beginners/question-answer-guide-astronomy|accessdate=4 April 2016|work=Sky at Night Magazine|publisher=BBC}}</ref>
