==M==

{{glossary}}

{{term|m}}
{{defn|A mass of a fermion. For example, ''m''<sub>''t''</sub> is the mass of the top quark ''t''.}}

{{term|M}}
{{defn|The mass of a boson; for example, ''M''<sub>''Z''</sub> is the mass of the Z-boson.}}

{{term|Majorana fermion}}
{{term|Majorana spinor}}
{{defn|{{main|Majorana fermion|Majorana spinor}} A fermion or spinor with a reality condition, in spacetimes of dimension   2, 3, 4 mod 8.}}

{{term|Majorana–Weyl fermion}}
{{term|Majorana–Weyl spinor}}
{{defn|{{main|Majorana–Weyl fermion|Majorana–Weyl spinor}} A half-spinor with a reality condition, in spacetimes of dimension 2 mod 8.}}

{{term|Mandelstam variable}}
{{defn|{{main|Mandelstam variables}} A sum or difference of two of the four incoming or outgoing momenta of a 2-particle interaction.}}

{{term|matrix theory}}
{{term|M(atrix) theory}}
{{defn|{{main|Matrix string theory}} One of several non-perturbative formulations of string theory or M-theory using infinite matrices.}}

{{term|M-brane}}
{{term|membrane}}
{{defn|{{main|Membrane (M-theory)}} A higher dimensional analogue of a string.}}

{{term|MC}}
{{defn|[[Monte Carlo integration]]}}

{{term|MCG}}
{{defn|{{main|Mapping class group}} }}

{{term|minimal model}}
{{defn|Certain solvable [[conformal field theories]].}}

{{term|Mirror symmetry (string theory)}}
{{defn|{{main|Mirror symmetry (string theory)}} A partly conjectural relation between a type IIA superstring theory compactified on a Calabi–Yau manifold and a type IIB superstring theory compactified on a different "mirror" Calabi–Yau manifold.}}

{{term|MLLA}}
{{defn|Modified leading logarithm approximation.}}

{{term|MNS}}
{{defn| [[Maki–Nakagawa–Sakata matrix]] for neutrino mixing}}

{{term|monopole}}
{{defn|{{main|Magnetic monopole|Dirac monopole|Wu–Yang monopole|'t Hooft–Polyakov monopole|Seiberg-Witten monopole|Monopole (mathematics)}}  A hypothetical particle similar to  a "magnet with only one pole".}}

{{term|Montonen–Olive duality}}
{{defn|{{main|Montonen–Olive duality}} An early case of [[S-duality]].}}

{{term|MS}}
{{defn|[[minimal subtraction]] (a renormalization scheme). {{overline|MS}} is the [[modified minimal subtraction scheme]].}}

{{term|MSM}}
{{defn|Abbreviation for [[minimal standard model]].}}

{{term|MSSM}}
{{defn|Abbreviation for [[minimal supersymmetric standard model]].}}

{{term|mSUGRA}}
{{defn|[[mSUGRA|Minimal model of supergravity]].}}

{{term|M-theory}}
{{defn|{{main|M-theory}}
An 11-dimensional theory introduced in the second string theory revolution to unify the 5 known superstring theories. The letter M has been said to stand for membrane, matrix, magic, mystery, monster, and so on.}}

{{term|MSW}}
{{defn|[[Mikheyev–Smirnov–Wolfenstein effect]] concerning neutrino oscillations in matter.}}

{{term|multiplet}}
{{defn|A linear representation of a Lie algebra or group.}}
{{defn|A collection of elementary particles corresponding to a basis of a representation.}}

{{glossary end}}

==N==

{{glossary}}

{{term|N}}
{{defn|no=1|The number of times each irreducible real spinor representation appears in the fermionic part of a [[supersymmetry algebra]] or [[super Minkowski space]]. It is often used in the description of an [[extended supersymmetry]] algebra, as in [[N=2 superconformal algebra]] and so on.}}
{{defn|no=2|A [[nucleon]], a baryon with 3 light quarks and isospin 1/2 (such as a [[proton]] or [[neutron]]).}}
{{defn|no=3|The number of some type of particle.}}

{{term|Nambu–Goto action}}
{{defn|{{main|Nambu–Goto action}} An action for strings, proportional to the area of the worldsheet.}}

{{term|NC}}
{{defn|Neutral current (weak interaction).}}

{{term|Neumann}}
{{defn|[[Neumann boundary condition]]s on an open string say that the momentum normal to the boundary of the world-sheet is zero. }}

{{term|neutralino}}
{{defn|{{main|Neutralino}} A hypothetical supersymmetric partner of a [[gauge boson]] with zero charge.}}

{{term|Neveu}}
{{defn|Named for [[André Neveu]].}}

{{term|Neveu–Schwarz algebra}}
{{defn|{{main|Neveu–Schwarz algebra}} A supersymmetric extension of the [[Virasoro algebra]], similar to the [[Ramond algebra]].}}

{{term|NG}}
{{defn|no=1|Short for Nambu–Goto, as in [[Nambu–Goto action]].}}
{{defn|no=2|Short for Nambu–Goldstone, as in [[Nambu–Goldstone boson]].}}

{{term|NLL}}
{{defn|Next to leading  logarithmic (term).}}

{{term|NLO}}
{{defn|Next to leading order (term).}}

{{term|NLSP}}
{{defn|next-to-lightest sypersymmetric particle}}

{{term|NMSSM}}
{{defn|[[Next-to-Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model]].}}

{{term|NNLL}}
{{defn|Next to next to leading  logarithmic (term).}}

{{term|NNLO}}
{{defn|Next to next to leading order (term).}}

{{term|NNNLL}}
{{defn|Next to next to next to leading  logarithmic (term).}}

{{term|no-ghost theorem}}
{{defn|{{main|No-ghost theorem}} A theorem stating that some hermitian form is positive semidefinite, in other words has no ghosts (negative norm vectors). The name is a word-play on [[no-go theorem]].}}

{{term|NR}}
{{defn|Non-relativistic}}

{{term|NRQCD}}
{{defn|Non-relativistic quantum chromodynamics}}

{{term|NS}}
{{defn|Neveu–Schwarz, especially the [[Neveu–Schwarz algebra]]}}

{{term|NS–NS}}
{{defn|A sector with Neveu–Schwarz conditions on left and right moving modes.}}

{{term|NS–R}}
{{defn|A sector with Neveu–Schwarz conditions on left moving modes and Ramond conditions on right moving modes.}}

{{term|NUT}}
{{defn|The initials of E. Newman, L. Tamburino, and T. Unti, mainly used in [[Taub–NUT vacuum]], a solution to Einsteins' equations.}}

{{glossary end}}

