==R==

{{glossary}}

{{term|R}}
{{defn|no=1|Short for Ramond, as in [[Ramond sector]].}}
{{defn|no=2| A curvature tensor {{main|Scalar curvature|Ricci curvature|Riemann curvature}}}}
{{defn|no=3|An abbreviation for right (moving modes).}}
{{defn|no=4|A radius}}
{{defn|no=5|'''R-symmetry''' is a symmetry of [[extended supersymmetry]] algebras.}}

{{term|Ramond}}
{{defn|Named for [[Pierre Ramond]].}}

{{term|Ramond algebra}}
{{defn|{{main|Ramond algebra}} A supersymmetric extension of the [[Virasoro algebra]], similar to the [[Neveu–Schwarz algebra]].}}

{{term|Rarita–Schwinger}}
{{defn|{{main|Rarita–Schwinger equation|Rarita–Schwinger field}} Refers to spin 3/2 fermions.}}

{{term|Regge}}
{{defn|no=1|Physicist [[Tullio Regge]].}}
{{defn|no=2|[[Regge trajectory]]: the squared mass of a hadronic resonance is roughly linear in the spin, with the constant of proportionality called the '''Regge slope'''.}}

{{term|revolution}}
{{defn|Any new idea in string theory. In particular the [[first superstring revolution]] refers to the discoveries in the mid 1980s such as the cancellation of gravitational anomalies and the [[heterotic string]], and the [[second superstring revolution]] refers to the discoveries in the mid 1990s, such as [[D-brane]]s, [[M-theory]], and matrix theory and the [[AdS/CFT correspondence]].}}

{{term|RG}}
{{defn|[[Renormalization group]].}}

{{term|RGE}}
{{defn|[[Renormalization group]] equation.}}

{{term|RH}}
{{defn|Right-handed}}

{{term|R–NS}}
{{defn|A sector with Ramond conditions on left moving modes and Neveu–Schwarz conditions on right moving modes.}}

{{term|RNS}}
{{defn|Ramond–Neveu–Schwarz, as in [[RNS formalism]], a way of incorporating supersymmetry into string theory that is supersymmetric on the world sheet.}}

{{term|R-parity}}
{{defn|{{main|R-parity}} A '''Z'''<sub>2</sub> symmetry of supersymmetric models.}}

{{term|R-R}}
{{defn|Short for [[Ramond–Ramond sector]]}}

{{glossary end}}

