[[File:Jakob Breyne.jpg|thumb|Jakob Breyne, Abbildung in Prodromi fasciculi rariorum plantarum primus et secundus, 1739]] '''Jacob Breyne''' (14 January 1637 – 25 January 1697) was a Polish merchant, [[naturalist]], and artist, born in [[Gdańsk|Danzig]] (Gdańsk),<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Breyne, Jacob (1637-1697) on JSTOR|url=http://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000032350|language=en|doi=10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000032350}}</ref> [[Royal Prussia]] (a fief of the [[Crown of Poland]]). He was the father of [[Johann Philipp Breyne]].
==Biography== Breyne was interested in plants from a young age, and collected specimens from around Danzig. He recorded where they were found and included [[ecological]] notes on each plant. He also collected specimens and plant illustrations from elsewhere, including the famous portfolio of paintings of [[Cape of Good Hope]] plants. These artworks were purchased in 1956, by Sir [[Ernest Oppenheimer]].
In 1661 Breyne made his first trip of many to the [[Netherlands]]. He became acquainted with prominent members of the community there who kept gardens which included some of the most beautiful and rare plants. A large number of the plants Breyne drew came from Van Beverningk, from Oud-Teilingen Sassenheim near [[Leiden]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.il/books?id=mkfdQ3l1YQUC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=Jacob%2BBreyne&source=bl&ots=S-4WFkEpU_&sig=ijKoHYnsNorp7QMoD6rfo0bHANU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9uZKdrdTXAhWDDuwKHT4PCFYQ6AEIVzAM#v=onepage&q=Jacob%2BBreyne&f=false|title=Botanical Exploration of Southern Africa|last=Gunn|first=Mary|last2=Codd|first2=L.E.W.|publisher=A.A. Balkema|year=1981|isbn=0869611291|location=Cape Town|pages=29–30}}</ref>
Breyne died in Danzig in 1697.
==Works== * ''Exoticarum aliarumque minus cognitarum plantarum centuria prima...'' (1674–1678)
